nigd Koninkrijk","Great Waltham, Essex, England":"Great Waltham, Essex, England"},"en":{"1342–2 May 1420":"1342–2 May 1420","1341–Female":"1341–Deceased","1342–1420":"1342–1420","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1352–Female":"1352–Deceased","1352–1382":"1352–1382","1376–Male":"1376–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1365–Female":"1365–Deceased","1403–1471":"1403–1471","1321–1392":"1321–1392","1325–1376":"1325–1376","July 1392":"July 1392","Abt 1403":"about 1403","1352":"1352","1341":"1341","1471":"1471","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1390":"1390","1403":"1403","1325":"1325","1376":"1376","1321":"1321","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1342":"1342","2 May 1420":"2 May 1420","of Great Waltha, , England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Great Waltham, Essex, England":"Great Waltham, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Drake","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>drake</i>, either ‘drake, male duck’ (compare   Duck  ) or ‘dragon’ (Old English <i>draca</i> ‘snake, dragon’ or the cognate Old Norse <i>draki</i>), including an emblematic dragon on a flag (compare   Dragon  ). Both the Old English and the Old Norse forms are from Latin <i>draco</i> ‘snake, monster’; its sense as a nickname is unclear but it may have had the sense ‘standard bearer’. The name was taken to Ireland in the 13th century and reinforced by later English settlers in the 17th century.","German: from Low German <i>drake</i> ‘dragon’, familiar as image on signboards, hence a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn with such signboard.","Dutch: variant, mostly Americanized and Flemish, of <b>Draak</b>, a cognate of 2 above, from <i>draak</i> (Middle Dutch <i>drake</i>) ‘dragon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Duck","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  .","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as an equivalent of <b>Lohan</b> (an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Leocháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Leochán</i>’) by mistranslation, as if from <i>lacha</i> ‘duck’.","North German (also <b>Dück</b>) and German (<b>Dück</b>): see   Dueck  ."]},{"name":"Drakes","meanings":["English: variant of   Drake  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: habitational name from Drax (Yorkshire). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>dræg</i> ‘portage, place where boats are dragged’ or <i>dræg</i> ‘drag net’, influenced by Old Norse <i>drag</i> ‘portage’, with a plural <i>drages</i> being shortened to <i>drags</i>, <i>Drax</i>.","In some cases perhaps an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) cognate in some other language."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":40,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Drake wa